revision.text:
'''TT353''' (Theban Tomb 353 – ''Theben, Grab 353'') is part of the two-section tomb complex of the steward and official {{ill|Senenmut|de|Senenmut|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, who played a significant role under the Egyptian queen {{ill|Hatshepsut|de|Hatschepsut|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. Construction of the tomb and its {{ill|TT71|de|TT71|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} chapel began in 1472 BCE, during the 7th regnal year of Hatshepsut. The {{ill|liturgical texts|de|Liturgie|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|transfiguration texts|de|Verklärung (Altes Ägypten)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>Liturgical text no. 7.</ref> found in Senenmut’s tomb date back to the {{ill|Old Kingdom of Egypt|de|Altes Reich|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and were initially reserved exclusively for {{ill|Pharaoh|de|Pharao|lt=the kings|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}.
By the {{ill|Middle Kingdom of Egypt|de|Mittleres Reich|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, these texts appeared in private rock-cut tombs, such as one in {{ill|Asyut|de|Asyut|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, during the reign of {{ill|Senusret I|de|Sesostris I.|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. Interestingly, Senenmut's tomb includes passages from the funerary texts of the Middle Kingdom, which were primarily used in cultic {{ill|recitations|de|Rezitation|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in the Old Kingdom without direct connections to funerary rites.
== Tomb Structure == [[File:Felsengräber Deir el-Bahari 08.jpg|thumb|Entrance of the tomb, left of the tomb of Nespekaschuti (TT312)]] The tomb is located in the {{ill|Theban Necropolis|de|Theben (Ägypten)|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} near the mortuary temple of the queen in {{ill|Deir el-Bahari|de|Deir el-Bahari|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. Egyptian tombs traditionally consist of two parts: an above-ground section (e.g., a {{ill|mastaba|de|Mastaba|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}), where the cult of the deceased took place, and an underground burial chamber for the {{ill|mummified|de|Mumifizierung im Alten Ägypten|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} remains. Typically, these parts are located close together. However, during the {{ill|New Kingdom of Egypt|de|Neues Reich|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, royal tombs began separating these areas. The burial chambers were placed in the {{ill|Valley of the Kings|de|Tal der Könige|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, while mortuary temples were constructed near the desert edge. This spatial separation was later copied by some officials.
Senenmut’s decorated tomb chapel {{ill|TT71|de|TT71|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} lacks a burial chamber, which was located in TT353. TT353, in contrast, does not feature an above-ground cult area and consists only of a long underground corridor leading to the burial chamber about 80 meters away.
The tomb is entirely carved into rock, with its entrance situated in a hollow east of the {{ill|Mortuary Temple of Hatshepsut|de|Totentempel der Hatschepsut|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. TT353 is approximately 90 meters long. A staircase descends from east to west. After 45 meters, a small door on the south side leads to a small chamber. The main corridor continues for another 10 meters, ending in Chamber A, the only decorated room in the tomb. The walls of Chamber A are lined with {{ill|limestone|de|Kalkstein|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} and patched with plaster in uneven areas. The centerpiece of the decoration is a {{ill|false door|de|Scheintür|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} on the western wall, partially inscribed with {{ill|Book of the Dead|de|Totenbuch|lt=Book of the Dead spell 148|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. Other wall surfaces are also inscribed with sunken {{ill|reliefs|de|Relief|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} containing Book of the Dead texts.
A staircase from Chamber A descends about 25 meters to an undecorated Chamber B. Another 10 meters further lies Chamber C, which is also undecorated.
== Astronomical Ceiling Decorations == [[File:Senenmut-Grab.JPG|thumb|The astronomical ceiling in the tomb]] A notable feature of TT353 is a decorated chamber approximately 50 meters inside the tomb. The walls and ceiling display {{ill|Book of the Dead|de|Ägyptisches Totenbuch|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} texts and unfinished {{ill|Egyptian calendar|de|Ägyptischer Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} astronomical entries, which are the earliest representative of the {{ill|part_of C dekan lists|de|Dekanlisten C|1=Decan List C|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, based on templates from the {{ill|A2 Decan Lists|de|Dekanlisten A2|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Middle Kingdom (Asyut).
A star clock dated to 1463 BCE within the tomb marks the departure from the traditional {{ill|diagonal star clocks|de|Diagonalsternuhr|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Middle Kingdom, inaugurating the Group C star clocks. The mentioned "{{ill|Seba-en-Sah|lt=Star of the King and Osiris|de|Seba-en-Sah|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}" {{ill|Culmination|de|Kulmination (Astronomie)|Culmination=Culmination|lt=culminated|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1463 BCE in ancient Egypt on {{ill|Season of the Inundation|de|Achet=Datierungen|lr=23 and 24 Achet III|lt=23 and 24 Achet III|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>14th and 15th November ({{ill|Julian calendar|de|Julianischer Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}).</ref>, symbolizing the rebirth of the deceased during the {{ill|Seventh Hour of the Night|de|Siebte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|7|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (midnight).<ref name=L136/>
These representations served as templates for ceiling decorations at least until the {{ill|Ramesside Period|de|Ramessidenzeit|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, as seen in the {{ill|Ramesside star clocks|de|Ramessidische Sternuhren|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}. The astronomical configurations in Senenmut’s tomb were copied exactly, despite changes in the {{ill|Egyptian civil calendar|de|Wandeljahr=Altes Ägypten|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} due to precession over time.<ref name=L136>Christian Leitz: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren'' (= ''Orientalia Lovaniensia Analecta,'' vol. 62). Uitgeverij Peeters en Departement Oriëntalistiek, Leuven 1995, ISBN 978-90-6831-669-8, pp.&nbsp;136 and 263–264.</ref> == See Also == * {{ill|List of Theban tombs|de|Liste der thebanischen Gräber|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}
== Literature == * Peter F. Dorman: ''The Monuments of Senenmut: Problems in Historical Methodology.'' Kegan Paul International, London/New York 1988, ISBN 0-7103-0317-3. * {{Interlanguage link|12=draft|Christian Leitz|fr|Christian Leitz|en|Christian Leitz|de|Christian Leitz (Ägyptologe)}}: ''Altägyptische Sternuhren.'' Peeters, Leuven 1995, ISBN 90-6831-669-9.
External Links * [https://www.maat-ka-ra.de/german/personen/senenmut/sen_t353.htm TT 353]
