== Astronomical Ceiling Decorations == [[File:Senenmut-Grab.JPG|thumb|The astronomical ceiling in the tomb]] A notable feature of TT353 is a decorated chamber approximately 50 meters inside the tomb. The walls and ceiling display {{ill|Book of the Dead|de|Ägyptisches Totenbuch|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} texts and unfinished {{ill|Egyptian calendar|de|Ägyptischer Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} astronomical entries, which are the earliest representative of the {{ill|part_of C dekan lists|de|Dekanlisten C|1=Decan List C|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}, based on templates from the {{ill|A2 Decan Lists|de|Dekanlisten A2|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Middle Kingdom (Asyut).
A star clock dated to 1463 BCE within the tomb marks the departure from the traditional {{ill|diagonal star clocks|de|Diagonalsternuhr|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} of the Middle Kingdom, inaugurating the Group C star clocks. The mentioned "{{ill|Seba-en-Sah|lt=Star of the King and Osiris|de|Seba-en-Sah|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}" {{ill|Culmination|de|Kulmination (Astronomie)|Culmination=Culmination|lt=culminated|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} in 1463 BCE in ancient Egypt on {{ill|Season of the Inundation|de|Achet=Datierungen|lr=23 and 24 Achet III|lt=23 and 24 Achet III|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>14th and 15th November ({{ill|Julian calendar|1=Julian calendar|de|Julianischer Kalender|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}}).</ref>, symbolizing the rebirth of the deceased during the {{ill|Seventh Hour of the Night|de|Siebte Nachtstunde (Altes Ägypten)|7|12=draft|12=draft|12=draft}} (midnight).<ref name=L136/>
